Date:9/14/2006 5:25:03 PM
From:Paul Senior
HTE/Forbes rant:
Adding more HTE. It's the cash distributions - which I hope aren't going to be
cut. That Grommit likes HTE and is in it, that's a positive (well, to me anyway
-g-)

I don't know anything of the Forbes/Lehmann Income Securities newsletter or
their HTE recommendation. I recently ended a free trial subscription to the
Forbes Growth letter though:

http://www.forbesinc.com/newsletters/fgi/

It was terrible. On a lot of levels. Imo.

First, some of the new stocks they were recommending I already bought at lower
prices. They were late, imo.
The time I had their newsletter, their performance seemed mediocre at best to
me. OTOH, my own performance with stocks then and now ain't so great either.
They'd recommend something, the stock seemed okay to me(fundamentals,
business), then in a subsequent letter, they'd recommend selling it -
apparently just because it didn't move or dropped.
You could not discern a method to their recommendations. Like they were writers
who just used their gut to pick stocks and to sell them. Seemed random to me.

On a basic level I ask (rhetorically), who are we? If we're here in the market
for a short time, to play around or maybe to try to make a killing and then get
out, that's one thing. But if we're like Mr. Buffett and plan to be buying (and
selling) stocks for decades, then we have to have a method for our buying and
selling. Imo, it cannot be by following a black box (fundamental and quant. as
determined by these newsletter people), where our buys and sells are
created/determined/recommended for us by methods of which we really have no
clue. And by newsletter people whose employment we cannot be assured of.
I learned nothing from the newsletter to help me be a better investor. "Buy
this, sell this" without giving education or methods does not help someone who
expects to be buying & selling stocks for many years. I'd say and feel the same
even if their picks which I mostly didn't understand, scooted up terrifically
in price. If an investor does not develop his/her own investing method but
rather is dependent on such a newsletter for advice/picks -- that's not a
recipe for the investor's long-term success. Imo anyway.
%EOM----------------------

