From:Paul Senior
Madharry, yes I've been considering that issue (When do you follow good value
funds into their individual selections?).

I'm specifically reflecting on Marty Whitman's picks. Somebody on his team
convinced them that buying tech stocks when they were low and you could buy
them something like 6-8x what they would earn when they achieved peak earnings,
was a good idea. So he/they bought several. For me of little faith, I had no
confidence that those stocks would ever see peak earnings again or that 8x peak
earnings wasn't a low. So I never bought. As best as I can guess, my decision
to avoid has been better than their decision back then to buy. (So far, and
maybe)

If though I look at Chinese real estate company, CHEUY, another Third Avenue
selection, and a stock they reported recently they were adding to, that's a
stock I have almost no idea what they could do in future (business or stock),
or their accounting, or their focus (management vs. stockholders' benefit). Yet
it's a stock I'm willing to bet the Third Avenue people have done a lot of
research on and are comfortable with. And that's one reason I'm will to ride
along with them on CHEUY.

I'd guess though, that in general you'd be right to look closely at value
funds' top selections, especially if you can buy around the price they got in.
